element_texts.text: My Dear Mr Taylor, I can not say farewell my heart is full and I do not want to say one word that sounds like parting. O how I shall miss you: the dear Lord only knows. I do not even know myself. but this I know, that I have a friend that sticketh closer than a brother and that he will never leave or forsake those who put their trust in him. I want to pray for me. Remember me at times in your prayers it will give me strength. May God bless you and yours with his [unclear] blessings. My prayers go with you all. Yours sorrowing E. C. Macomber.

element_texts.text: unclear unclear May ??80. My Dear Mr Taylor. I am truly glad that you had so pleasant a day for your trip to Hartford?. It seemed more cheerful than a dark and dismal day would. But I assure you that it was gloomy enough to me. My heart was sad and heavy, for you who I love so feverently, and have loved so long had left me. And I seemed to be alone. No. Not alone for their is one who is with us always even unto the end. And while I am sorrowing, I rejoice in the goodness of our Lord.

element_texts.text: I thank God that he sent you to this field of labour, and that he sent you to me. to lead me to Him. I rejoice in your successful ministry, in your patient, loving and self sacrificing work for your master. He who unclear unclear, has already rewarded you, but the full reward will be received when you hear well done good and faithful servant enter though into the joy of the Lord. We are having fine weather, quite unclear and dry. beginning to need rain. The wind is blowing strong to day and the air is filled with dust. Have not learned who is to preach for us on Sunday
